Precision and word choice.

At B level you already know enough words to say almost anything. The C-level jump is not more words. It is reaching for the exact one. Precision is what makes writing feel sharp, and speech feel sure of itself. Vagueness is what leaves correct English feeling flat.

This notebook works on the form layer from notebook one, zoomed all the way in to the single word. There are five levers. The attitude a word carries, the partners a word expects, freeing the verb trapped inside a noun, cutting the words that earn nothing, and matching the word to the room.

Connotation. Words carry an attitude.

Every word has a denotation, which is its dictionary meaning, and a connotation, which is the feeling and judgement riding along with it. Synonyms share the denotation, and they split on the connotation. So choosing between two synonyms is really choosing a stance.

Think of all the words that mean thin. Slim and slender sound attractive and deliberate. Lean sounds fit and athletic. Underweight is clinical and neutral. Skinny is slightly negative, a bit too thin. And gaunt sounds unwell and hollow. Same body, five different opinions about it. The listener hears the opinion whether you intended it or not. So the skill is making sure the word leaks the attitude you actually hold.

Here are more pairs that trip people up. Each pair shares a meaning, but flips the judgement. Confident, versus arrogant. Assertive, versus pushy. Thrifty, versus stingy. Curious, versus nosy. Determined, versus stubborn. And childlike, versus childish. The left side admires. The right side disapproves. But the underlying fact is the same.

Here is an everyday image. Two shirts cover you equally well, but one says job interview and the other says beach. In the same way, a word can fit the meaning, and still wear the wrong message.

Collocation. Words travel in packs.

Some words simply expect certain partners. The pairing is not a grammar rule. It is just what sounds native. Get the word right but the partner wrong, and a fluent listener flinches, even though nothing is technically incorrect.

For example. You make a mistake, you do not do a mistake. You do your homework, you do not make your homework. Rain is heavy, not strong. Coffee is strong, not powerful. You commit a crime. You pay attention. You take a risk. In each case the meaning would survive the wrong partner, but it would sound off.

This is the single biggest tell of an advanced but non-native speaker. The grammar is flawless, and the word partnerships are a half step off.

Intensifiers collocate too. You cannot swap them freely. Something is highly likely, not very likely, which sounds weaker. You are bitterly disappointed, not strongly disappointed. You are deeply concerned. You are fully aware. Something is utterly ridiculous. Each strong adverb belongs to particular adjectives.

The way to build this is to collect chunks, not single words. Store the phrase, make a decision, as one single unit, the way you once stored a single word. That is how native speakers carry it.

Rescue the verb trapped in the noun.

Here is a quiet drag on advanced writing. You take a perfectly good verb, freeze it into a noun, and then prop it up with a weak helper verb like make, do, give, conduct, provide, or reach. The result is longer, colder, and slower.

Listen to the difference. Make a decision, versus simply, decide. Conduct an investigation, versus investigate. Give consideration to, versus consider. Reach a conclusion, versus conclude. Provide assistance, versus help. Carry out an analysis, versus analyse. The single strong verb is shorter and carries more energy every time.

Take a full sentence. We will conduct a review of the data and reach a decision. That is eleven words. Now thaw the verbs. We will review the data and decide. Seven words, the same meaning, and far more drive.

The verb is where a sentence's energy lives, and burying it inside a noun freezes it. This is not a ban. Sometimes the action genuinely is the topic, as in, the decision was unpopular. Overuse is the problem, not the form itself. So here is the habit to build. Whenever you write make, do, give, or conduct, followed by a noun, check whether that noun is a verb in hiding.

Cut the words that earn nothing.

Precision is as much subtraction as selection. Here is the test. Delete the word. If the meaning survives, it was filler.

First, intensifier inflation. The word very, attached to a weak word, is weaker than one exact word. Very angry is just furious. Very tired is exhausted. Very big is enormous. Very small is tiny. Very important is crucial. Very surprised is astonished. And note that very unique, or very perfect, are nonsense, because those words are already absolute.

Second, filler nouns. Words like thing, stuff, aspect, factor, and area. A specific noun is almost always hiding behind them. The financial side beats the money aspect.

Third, dead phrases. Long wind-ups that say nothing. In order to, is just, to. Due to the fact that, is just, because. At this point in time, is just, now. In the event that, is just, if. Has the ability to, is just, can. And, it is important to note that, can usually just be deleted, so you simply say the thing.

None of these make you sound advanced. They make the reader wait. Now, deliberate and careful hedging is a genuine skill, and that is notebook four. This section is about the accidental padding, not the chosen kind.

Match the word to the room.

English carries two vocabularies stacked on top of each other. A short, blunt, warm Anglo-Saxon core, and a longer, cooler, more formal Latin and French layer that arrived later. Most everyday ideas have one of each. Buy, or purchase. Start, or commence. End, or terminate. Help, or assist. Ask, or enquire. Need, or require. Get, or obtain. Enough, or sufficient.

Here is the trap, and it is the most common jump-to-mastery mistake. Reaching for the fancy word, just to sound advanced. It backfires. Over-formal writing sounds pompous, distant, even evasive. Listen. We will commence the procedure to obtain the required authorisation. Now hear the plain version. We will start getting the approval we need. The plain words carry warmth and trust.

Higher register is not better. It is just higher. Mastery is to default to the plain word, and reach for the formal one only when the situation truly calls for it. A legal notice, a careful complaint, a formal report. Knowing both, and choosing on purpose, is the whole game. Notebook six takes this from single words up to the tone of a whole message.

To finish, the notebook gives you a set of flabby but correct sentences to tighten yourself, using these levers. Try each one before you check the suggested rewrite. Your version does not have to match. If you cut filler, freed a verb, or fixed a collocation, you turned the right dial.
